>
  <p>
    <strong>Direct answer:</strong> A certificate of deposit (CD) pays interest when you agree to leave funds on
    deposit for a stated term. In the United States, banks and credit unions disclose deposit rates under the Truth in
    Savings Act (Regulation DD). The figure used for comparison shopping is usually the
    <strong>annual percentage yield (APY)</strong>, which already reflects compounding. Nestfigure’s free
    <a href="/cd-calculator/">CD calculator</a> applies standard compound-interest formulas for education—it is not a
    bank quote.
  </p>

  <div class="key-takeaways card">
    <h2 class="takeaways-title">Key takeaways</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <strong>CFPB:</strong> a CD is a savings product with a set term; early withdrawal means a penalty fee (
        <a
          href="https://www.consumerfinance.gov/ask-cfpb/what-is-a-certificate-of-deposit-cd-en-917/"
          rel="noopener noreferrer"
          target="_blank">Ask CFPB CD explainer</a
        >).
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>APY vs interest rate:</strong> APY reflects compounding; the interest rate does not (Regulation DD / 12
        CFR Part 1030).
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Sample math only:</strong> $10,000 at a labeled 4.50% effective annual yield for one year → $450 interest
        / $10,450 balance under Nestfigure assumptions—not a live bank offer.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Insurance:</strong> CFPB states bank CDs may be FDIC-insured and credit-union CDs NCUA-insured up to
        $250,000 under applicable rules.
      </li>
    </ul>
  </div>

