  />

  <h2 id="frictions">Early withdrawal and other real-world frictions</h2>
  <p>
    The CFPB states that withdrawing money from a CD early means paying a penalty fee to the bank. When shopping, the
    CFPB advises comparing term, interest rate, and the early-withdrawal penalty. Nestfigure’s calculator does
    <strong>not</strong> model penalties, bonuses, tiered rates, or taxes.
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Early withdrawal penalties (product-specific)</li>
    <li>Promotional or step-up rates</li>
    <li>Account fees and minimum balances</li>
    <li>Tax on interest income (depends on your situation and tax law)</li>
    <li>Issuer day-count conventions (for example, how partial periods are treated)</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Deeper guide:
    <a href="/guides/cd-early-withdrawal/">CD early withdrawal &amp; penalties</a>.
  </p>

  <h2>Deposit insurance (CFPB summary)</h2>
  <p>
    The same CFPB CD explainer states that CDs offered by banks are insured up to $250,000 by the FDIC, and those
    offered by credit unions are insured up to $250,000 by the NCUA. Confirm coverage for your ownership structure with
    <a href="https://edie.fdic.gov/" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank">FDIC EDIE</a>
    or
    <a href="https://ncua.gov/consumers/share-insurance-coverage" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank"
      >NCUA share insurance materials</a
    >.
  </p>

